'''W. Wilson White '''(1906 – 1964) was a prominent attorney in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] and served as the first [[United States Assistant Attorney General]] for the [[United States Department of Justice Civil Rights Division]] from 1957 to 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov/crt/speeches/historical_perspective.pdf |title=The Department of Justice's Civil Rights Division: A Historical Perspective as the Division Nears 50, Remarks by Wan Kim, Mar. 22, 2006}}</ref> He was the [[United States Attorney]] for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania from 1953 to 1957.<ref>[http://politicalgraveyard.com/bio/white9.html#868.48.89 The Political Graveyard]</ref> White was also a partner in the law firm [[White and Williams LLP]] which was founded by his father, [[Thomas Raeburn White]].<ref>"Funeral Services This Afternoon for W. Wilson White" The Legal Intelligencer, November 13, 1964</ref>

